 others; and the universal status of spirit, gender, and empire in the worlds of Vaughan, Donne, and the dastan (tale) of Chouboli, a Rajasthani princess. Together, these essays make the case that to address what it takes to make a world in the early modern period requires the kinds of thinking exemplified by theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aLiterary Studies. 4aRenaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aMarlowe.  aRenaissance Literature.  aShakespeare.  aWorlds.  amateriality.  asexuality.  asovereignty.1 aBovilsky, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawson, Brent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Marcie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, Marcie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGil, Daniel Juan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlimp, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldberg, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunin, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuzner, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatz, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaxwell, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenon, Madhavi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNewman, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert